virtualization on linux..

egrep -c '(vmx|svm)' /proc/cpuinfo
lsmod | grep kvm
sudo adduser $USER kvm
kvm-ok

On VirtualBox:

    Power off the VM.
    Go to Settings → System → Processor.
    Enable Enable Nested VT-x/AMD-V.
If you are using other hypervisors (e.g., VirtualBox, Hyper-V, VMware), they may conflict with KVM. If you have Hyper-V enabled on Windows, for instance, you won’t be able to use KVM inside WSL2 or any other virtual machines.

    Disable Hyper-V if necessary:
        Open PowerShell as Administrator and run:

        bash

bcdedit /set hypervisorlaunchtype off

Restart your computer.
---------------

sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade

sudo apt install qemu-kvm libvirt-daemon-system libvirt-clients bridge-utils virtinst virt-manager
---verify----

lsmod | grep kvm
sudo adduser $USER libvirt
sudo adduser $USER kvm

sudo systemctl enable libvirtd
sudo systemctl start libvirtd

---Create a virtual machine

sudo virt-install \
  --name ubuntu-vm \
  --ram 2048 \
  --vcpus 2 \
  --disk size=10 \
  --os-variant ubuntu20.04 \
  --cdrom /path/to/ubuntu.iso \
  --network bridge=virbr0 \
  --graphics vnc

----
sudo virt-manager
virsh list --all



